`crates/` is the workspace root: a set of independent, standalone binary crates (plus one shared library, `ctx-core`) that together form the `ctx` context-management toolchain — scanning, summarizing, verifying, sandboxing, and briefing. Depending on this level means picking a specific crate's binary/CLI surface or the `ctx-core` library; there is no cross-crate code sharing beyond `ctx-core`, and no shared build logic described here.

The crates split cleanly by pipeline stage: `ctx-scan` walks a repo and detects staleness, `ctx-summarize` generates and rolls up `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files (the same artifacts `ctx-scan` tracks and `ctx-context` serves), `ctx-context` is the read-only CLI/hook that resolves and renders that chain, `ctx-verify` runs external checks and reports results, `ctx-cage` sandboxes process execution, and `ctx-brief` turns backlog items into executor briefs via `claude` CLI passes. `ctx-core` supplies path-safety and hash-sidecar schema shared by `ctx-scan` and `ctx-context`.

The load-bearing cross-crate coupling is data-format, not code: the `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` file format and the `.context` mirror-path convention are produced by `ctx-summarize`, tracked by `ctx-scan`, and consumed by `ctx-context` — a schema or path-layout change in one must be checked against the other two, since nothing enforces this at compile time across crate boundaries. Each crate otherwise repeats the same internal pattern independently: strict `main → cli → runner` layering, an `Fs`/tool trait seam faked in its own integration tests, and a test suite that hardcodes wire-level details (flags, prompt filenames, model strings) that must be updated in lockstep with `src/` changes — this is a convention shared across crates, not shared code.

No intent.md exists at this level, so no divergence can be assessed.